# Detection Templates

## Validation

Always validate before committing:
- **Splunk**: `contentctl validate` (activate venv first)
- **Sigma**: `sigma check rule.yml` or use pySigma
- **Elastic**: detection engine built-in validation

## Splunk Detection YAML

Write to: `$SECURITY_CONTENT_PATH/detections/<kind>/<name>.yml`

Key rules:
- `rba:` section is top-level (NOT inside tags)
- Filter macro: `snake_case(detection_name)_filter`
- Data source names must match `data_sources/*.yml` entries exactly
- File name must be snake_case of the `name` field

## Sigma Rule

Standard YAML with: title, id, status, level, description, logsource, detection, falsepositives, tags (attack.tactic, attack.tXXXX.XXX).

## KQL Analytics Rule (Sentinel)

Write KQL with comment headers for title and MITRE mapping. Use DeviceProcessEvents, SigninLogs, etc. For programmatic deployment, wrap in YAML with `queryFrequency`, `severity`, `tactics`, `relevantTechniques`, and `entityMappings`.

## Elastic Security Rule (TOML)

Elastic rules use TOML format with `[metadata]`, `[rule]`, and `[[rule.threat]]` sections. Set `type = "eql"` for EQL queries or `type = "query"` for KQL/Lucene. Always include `[[rule.threat.technique]]` and `[rule.threat.tactic]` blocks for MITRE mappings.

## Story Template (Splunk)

Stories must be CONCISE: 17-19 lines total. Description 3-5 sentences, narrative 5-8 sentences.

## Reference Lists

Detection Types: TTP, Anomaly, Hunting, Baseline, Correlation
Security Domains: endpoint, network, threat, identity, access, audit, cloud
Asset Types: Endpoint, Network, Cloud Instance, AWS Account, Azure Tenant, etc.
